


	
        Why is there a system sound called Asterisk? What sound does an Asterisk make anyway?          Raymond Chen        
            
            November 8th, 20223 2
		
        A Twitter user who goes by the name  ASwisstone asked  why there is a system sound called Asterisk. Yup there it is:  System.Media.SystemÂ­Sounds.Asterisk. What sound does an Asterisk make anyway?
If you dig into the reference source, youâ€™ll see that the SystemSound.Play method  calls SafeNativeMethods.MessageBeep with the corresponding value MB_ICONASTERISK.
Okay, so this sound is intended to accompany an asterisk icon. But what is the asterisk icon?
The MB_ prefix may be a clue. These are values that you can pass to the MessageBox function to specify what icon should be shown in the message box, and the sound plays when a message box is shown with the corresponding icon.
The documentation says that MB_ICONÂ­ASTERISK produces â€œAn icon consisting of a lowercase letter i in a circle.â€
Wait a second, thatâ€™s not an asterisk! It seems that each time we peel back a layer of the onion, the story just gets more confusing!
The story starts to become less murky when you notice that the MB_ICONÂ­ASTERISK constant has the same numerical value (and same description) as the MB_ICONÂ­INFORMATION constant.
Okay, now we can put the pieces of the story together.
Once upon a time, there was MB_ICONÂ­ASTERISK, which presumably showed an asterisk icon. At some point, the asterisk was replaced with an information symbol ğŸ›ˆ and an alternate name for the flag was invented: MB_ICONÂ­INFORMATION.
To test this theory, I dug through the  pcjs.org archive of old versions of Windows maintained by my retired colleague and doughnut enthusiast Jeff Parsons (Previously about Jeff.)
And lo and behold, we can see it in action: Fire up  Windows 1.0, launch Notepad, and then hit Ctrl+F to call up the Search dialog. Search for some nonsense string and hit Enter.

The asterisk was also used in Windows 2.0 (see for yourself), but Windows 3.0 changed the icon to the information symbol. Nevertheless, the programmatic name remained â€œAsteriskâ€, for compatibility.
Bonus chatter: Mind you, Windows 1.0 didnâ€™t have support for any sounds aside from the plain old beep from the built-in PC speaker. Multimedia sound support didnâ€™t arrive until Windows 3.0.
Bonus chatter 2: At the same time that Asterisk became Information, the Hand was changed to a Stop sign.Â¹ The Exclamation didnâ€™t want to be left out of the party, even though its icon didnâ€™t change, but at least it was renamed to Warning.
Â¹ In Windows 95, the stop sign changed to a filled red circle with a white X.

        
                

        
		
                

            
            
                
